    "# Research Question"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Did the characteristics of passengers on the Titanic, such as ticket class, age, and gender, affect an individual's survivability?\n",
    "- Considering the women and children first rule, how does that correlate with survival statistics, specifically looking at the \"adult male\" column of the data?\n",
    "- Did richer passengers, i.e. those who purchased higher deck or class tickets for higher prices have a higher survival rate than those who purchased cheaper tickets?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The RMS Titanic was a British ocean liner infamous for its sinking after colliding with an iceberg on April 15, 1912, resulting in ~1500 people out of the 2200+ passengers dying from the wreck. The data set we are analyzing includes information on 891 passengers, including their passenger class, age, sex, and their accompaniment. Even though considered a catastrophic event, which are usually described as random or indiscriminate, research consistently shows that social factors shape survival outcomes. Disaster research reveals that survival is influenced by social factors, such as socioeconomic status (SES), age, and gender, rather than pure chance. \n",
    "\n",
    "Similar studies:\n",
    "\n",
    "A paper from Bowdoin College highlights that the Titanic, like many disasters, had \"differential effects\" in which survival and suffering were unequally distributed across class, age, and gender lines. It emphasized that first-class passengers had a survival rate of about 62%, compared to 41% in second class and only 25% in third class (Bowdoin), showcasing stark SES differences and translation to better survival hood. The aper theorizes that the higher status translates into better access to information, lifeboats, and life-saving opportunities.  The paper also incorporates a diagram of the Titanic, showcasing that third class passengers were located lower and at the ends of the boat, second class lower middle, and first class upper middle. This diagram allows for the inference that if the boat were sinking, the first-class passengers had more time to reach life-saving measures. The same piece showcases that women and children had much higher rates of survival, with 75 and 50 percent, respectively, while men only had about 20% survival. This follows suit with the order Captain E.J. Smith gave to officers, \"women and children first.\" The paper also mentions that certain officers interpreted these orders differently, with Officer Lightroller taking the order to mean women and children only, lowering lifeboats even before full capacity to prioritize women and children's survival.\n",
    "\n",
    "In a more formal analysis, Frey, Heggli, and Osterloh used individual-level Titanic data to test how economic resources, age, and gender affected the probability of survival. Aside from reconfirming that class and gender played a large role in the probability of survival, they showed age mattered as well. People in their \"prime\" (ages around 15-35) were more likely to survive than older passengers (Frey et al.), suggesting that physical mobility and stamina interacted with the other categories to shape outcomes.\n",
    "\n",
    "A study similar to our proposed topic, but with a slightly different data set, concluded that gender was, in fact, the key determining factor in survivability.1 Because this is a historical topic, we can safely assume that there will be no issues with outdated data or analysis, but the data sets being analyzed may have varying results. Despite being the same size, with 891 passengers, the data set we are analyzing has some additional information that may reveal more nuance in the death statistics. Additionally, the individuals may be different, meaning a different population of the Titanic survivors was sampled.\n",
    "\n",
    "An article from the NIH states that, despite the widespread belief of prioritizing women and children in maritime accidents, women in fact have a significant survival disadvantage in these situations 2. It further asserts that despite the survival rate of women on the Titanic being significantly higher, in the grander scheme of maritime accidents reflects the opposite.\n",
    "\n",
    "Citations:\n",
    "\n",
    "\"Analysis of Titanic Survival Data\", ttsteiger.github.io/projects/titanic_report.html. Accessed 4 Feb. 2026.\n",
    "\n",
    "Elinder, Mikael, and Oscar Erixson. \"Gender, Social Norms, and Survival in Maritime Disasters.\" Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America, U.S. National Library of Medicine, 14 Aug. 2012, pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3421183/.\n",
    "\n",
    "Bowdoin. \"Disproportionate Devastation | Titanic.\" Bowdoin, 2020, courses.bowdoin.edu/history-2203-fall-2020-kmoyniha/reflection/.\n",
    "\n",
    "Frey, Bruno S, et al. \"Surviving the Titanic Disaster: Economic, Natural and Social Determinants.\" Escholarship.org, Feb. 2009, escholarship.org/uc/item/6h24b1vt."
   ]
  },
  {
