   "source": [
    "### Data overview\n",
    "\n",
    "Dataset Name: Titanic Dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "Link to the dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/shraddha4ever20/titanic-datset \n",
    "\n",
    "Number of observations: 891\n",
    "\n",
    "Number of variables: 15\n",
    "\n",
    "Description of the variables most relevant to this project: 13\n",
    "\n",
    "Descriptions of any shortcomings this dataset has with respect to the project: This dataset has some null values for the passenger ages. It also contains some repeated data in different formats (e.g., passenger class in both numeric and string formats). While this is not inherently a downside, it forces us to decide which format works better for our analysis purposes.\n",
    "\n",
    "The primary dataset we selected from Kaggle is well-suited for our research question since it includes individual-level information on survival, age, sex, ticket class, and fare for 891 passengers. This allows us to look at how socioeconomic status (class and fare), age, and gender all influenced survival outcomes. Although this dataset represents a portion rather than the full passenger and crew list, it is large enough to support meaningful statistical analysis while remaining manageable for our project. Each row in the kaggle dataset corresponds to a single passenger and includes variables such as survival status (0 = did not survive, 1 = survived), passenger class (which we treate as a SES indicator), sex (nale/female), age, fare (ticket price, another SES indicator), and a few additional identifiers which wont be used but could be linked to external sources for deeper context.\n",
    "\n",
    "In an ideal scenario, we would work with a complete manifest that includes all passengers and crew, precise cabin locations, lifeboat assignments, and verified socioeconomic status indicators directly sourced from the original passenger documents. That dataset would have helped to reduce sampling bias and enable more detailed modeling of how physical location on the ship and social status affected the changes of reaching a lifeboat. Our current Kaggle dataset approximates this ideal by providing demographic and class variables, but is limited by missing ages and the absence of detailed location or income information.\n",
    "\n",
    "There are a few complementary real-world datasets and sources that could help us move closer to this scenario. For example, the Safe-DS Titanic dataset includes cabin numbers, which would allow us to incorporate more precise spatial information about where passengers were located on the ship at the time of impact. Wikipedia's compiled passenger list and summaries provide additional attributes that can help us, such as nationality and, in some cases, lifeboat assignment. Nationality can be used to explore potential discrimination or differences in survival by country of origin, while lifeboat assignments can help reconstruct evacuation patterns. Together, these sources could be integrated with the Kaggle dataset to create a more complete picture, but our core analysis for how class, age, and gender influenced survival, which the Kaggle dataset already holds the essential variables we need.\n",
    "\n",
    "\"Titanic - Safe-DS Datasets.\" Safeds.com, 2026, datasets.safeds.com/en/stable/datasets/titanic/. Accessed 16 Feb. 2026.\n",
    "\n",
    "\"Passengers of the Titanic.\" Wikipedia, 12 Feb. 2021, en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Passengers_of_the_Titanic."
   ]
